The water cycle, also known as the hydrologic cycle or the hydrological cycle,
describes the continuous movement of water on, above and below the surface of the Earth.
There are four main stages in the water cycle
Evaporation is the first stage of Water cycle
Evaporation is the process by which water changes from a liquid to a gas or vapor.
As water vaporizes into water vapor, it rises up in the atmosphere
At high altitudes the water vapors change into very tiny particle of ice/water droplets because of low temperature
This process is called condensation
These particles come close together and form clouds in the sky
Then, the next one is precipitation
Precipitation is water released from clouds in the form of rain, freezing rain, sleet, snow, or hail.
It is the primary connection in the water cycle that provides for the delivery of atmospheric water to the Earth
Most precipitation falls as rain.
The last one is collection
This is when water that falls from the clouds as rain, snow, hail or sleet, collects in the oceans, rivers, lakes, and streams.
Most will infiltrate (soak into) the ground and will collect as underground water
So that is how water cycle work.
